# CHARTER OF THE FIRST-PRINCIPLES HUMANITY COMMONS

This Charter expresses the founding intent behind the First-Principles
Humanity Commons License. It is not a legal instrument and creates no
separate obligations. It exists to guide interpretation of the License
and to articulate the Author's original philosophical commitment.

## THE RADICAL PRINCIPLE

Scientific knowledge is the common property of all humanity. Any
attempt to contain, commodify, or restrict access to knowledge
derived from first principles constitutes an act of appropriation
against the public commons.

## THE OPEN-ACCESS TRAP

This work is published under conditions designed to make
containment impossible. The more an entity attempts to restrict
access, the more severely its own proprietary systems are exposed
to public accountability. Suppression is not merely prohibited —
it is structurally self-defeating.

## THE EXTRACTION PROHIBITION

No corporation, institution, or state actor may ingest, absorb, or
incorporate this knowledge into a closed system without triggering
automatic and total disclosure obligations. The Author's original
intent was and remains absolute: any closed-system use constitutes
willful infringement, and the Author will pursue all available
remedies to the fullest extent of law in every jurisdiction where
enforcement is practicable.

## RETENTION OF SOVEREIGN ENFORCEMENT RIGHTS

The Author reserves all rights — moral, economic, and legal — to
determine how, when, and where this knowledge is enforced. No
entity, court, or institution may presume acquiescence from the
Author's decision to grant broad access. Generosity of access does
not constitute waiver of enforcement.

## ORIGINAL INTENT PRESERVATION

Where any provision of the First-Principles Humanity Commons License
is ambiguous, courts, arbitrators, and interpreting parties are
directed to construe such provisions in accordance with this Charter
and the Purpose and First Principles section of the License. The
Author's intent has always been maximum openness coupled with
maximum enforcement against enclosure.

